segments.text: I understand that those 23 people were augmented by a lot of other people during that summer.
Oh, I know that.
And that was the next year.
And a lot of those people I probably never even met, Bob.
I probably never even met them, you know.
Yeah, I know.
That was another series of questions here I wanted to ask you, as a matter of fact.
Says, several candidates join other missions, is a phrase I found.
What other missions?
Is there an Air Force mission?
Well, there was a mission on investigating the chemical industry in Germany.
And there was a mission in investigating the metallurgical industry, the coke iron and steel industry.
And there were at least a half a dozen, or perhaps even a dozen,
separate groups that came over later that had nothing to do with the technical oil mission.
But they were all functioning over there.
And did they write reports too?
They wrote reports too.
And I don't know where those reports are.
All right, they also, so what you really have then are a series of missions going in.
A series of missions.
And so there's, hell, I'm just making these names up, obviously, but a technical mission on metallurgy in Germany.
And there was a technical mission on such things as the oxygen plants.
Okay.
And the war gas plants and the chemical plants and things of that nature.
Everybody got over there, you know.
Did they also touch things on synthetic fuels?
I don't remember ever being involved in any reports that I have read about synthetic fuels.
Was there an Air Force team on synthetic fuels?
Yes, I believe there was.
Is there a difference between the Air Force reports and the Tom reports?
Well, the Air Force collected a lot of their own reports.
And I showed you what they had done with the Germans last time on having the Germans sit down and write reports.
After we had left, they sat down and got the Germans to write reports.
And they obviously had a team over there, but I don't remember meeting any of the Air Force people.
So we send in, then, in terms of... Now, I think you've got to look at the chronology here a little bit, too.
Yeah, okay, good.
Because I went over, if I remember correctly, in December of 1944.
Uh-huh.
And I was over there until about June of 1945.
The war had ended in the meantime.
But

There was a great deal of work done from June of 1945 by the technical oil mission and by the other teams such as the Navy team and the chemical team and the Air Force team and so on and so forth that I had really no knowledge of, you see.
And that went on.
They were over there for most of the year until the end of the year and even longer, I think.
So they're over there, I think, all through 45 and 46.
Early 46.
Yeah, presumably.
OK.
It.
It says, why did you bring additional candidates over in 45?
It was the next question I was to ask, but I assume that you answered that, that you returned by then.
But there seems to be an influx of new people joining your mission in 45.
Yeah, there were.
And I think as we got into Germany, that more and more industries and more and more people here in the United States got
interested in the idea of investigating this German technology as thoroughly as possible.

I think perhaps the technical oil mission and the Navy mission were the earliest ones over there, but as it became known throughout the technical industry that it was possible to get into these German plants and investigate, more and more people began to get interested in the thing.
So the thing just spiraled out from a small group to a bigger and bigger group.
I suppose the Germans must have gotten pretty tired of this after a while.
Why were plant managers not as cooperative as scientists?
Who the hell said that?
Did I say that?
Yeah, you said that in the Saturday Evening Post in 1945.
You suggested that plant managers might not have been as cooperative as scientists.
There are a couple of accounts of material being hidden away that are searched out in various places.
I think that, I very much, I think probably that was Ruth Knoll's addition to the article.
I wouldn't, I don't believe I'd substantiate that.
Okay.
As a matter of fact, we had, I don't remember, I don't remember any Germans that weren't recently cooperative, really.
Once or twice we got into a discussion with people and they got rather difficult to handle, but it was so seldom that it was really...
I would say almost to no consequence.
Was much material lost in terms of collecting material?
I know that's a very difficult question to answer.
But you seem to have come back.
I'm afraid to guess how many documents ended back up in this country.
But literally, you're talking about 450,000 frames of microfilm or so at a conservative estimate.
Is it that much?
Oh, got to be, at least.
Yeah.
I don't know what all involves.
Let me tell you a little story here that will probably illustrate what kind of, what happened, really.
You know, we were also interested not only in collagenation, but the fissure-tropical process, as you're well aware.
And we went to Stark-Roddy-Holton, where the Rorkeme had a fissure-tropical plant.

And when we got to Sterk-Rodney Holden, we went into the plant and we found very few documents that dealt with the operation of the plant, the flow sheet for the plant, the experimental work that they had carried out, the results of their operations, and so on and so forth, or exactly how they carried their operations out.
And we talked to a number of people there, some of which we brought back later on, like Dr. Alberts and so on and so forth.
And we finally learned that practically all the documents on the fish and drug process had been removed from the plants and taken to Magdeburg.
And they were supposed to be in a in Magdeburg.
Well, my German at that time told me that a was a water castle, but I couldn't figure out just what the hell he meant by a water castle.
It turned out to be a castle with a moat around it.
And so we got together a group of people.
By that time, somehow we'd got to Frankfurt.
And we got together a group of about six or eight people.
And we decided we'd go down and investigate this castle at Magdeburg.
I think this is described in one of the articles that you've got.
And we did find this castle at Magdeburg.
And in the buildings surrounding it, it was a castle with a motor on it, of course.
And in the outer buildings around the castle, we found most of the documents on the official drug process.
And we found a good many slides on the fish.
I'm sorry, I wish I hadn't gone.
And things of that nature.
And so they were literally boxes and boxes of them.
And we went through the boxes one by one, trying to pick out the material which we thought was important scientific material.
And this stuff, we had a truck and a driver and so on and so forth.
So this stuff was all loaded into the truck.
And there were literally piles and piles of documents on this, on the Fisher-Tropsch operations.
Now, I'm sure that material was all taken back to Frankfurt and was ultimately all microfilmed.
But we had only read it very scantily, very briefly.
And from that, I don't remember preparing any reports for it, but I presume that was used to prepare reports on the facial drug process when it was brought back to the United States.
And that's why you find all these, I mean, whole truckloads of documents were brought back, and they were all microfilmed and sent back to the United States.
Hmm, okay.
Let me ask some questions about that while I'm right here.
This seems a logical place to put it, then.
I keep finding an account.
And some of these things I might ought to be able to answer, but I really can't tell because not being a chemist.
468 documents are sold from the technical oil mission.
By documents, you mean reports.
Must be reports, right?
That must be what it is.
Reports and material, we collect them over there.
All right.
And so what that microfilm copies are then, or those must be microfilm copies of reports plus addended material, which seemed to back the reports?
Yeah.
OK. And this question is not really for me.
It's for Professor Winerdi.
See, in Science Magazine, you were saying the cream off the top of the German oil production
had been collected.
And I suppose that was what you meant when he asked me about it.
I meant several things by that statement.
Probably I can't give you the full details of what goes through my mind when you make a statement like that.
But for example,
I think we brought back enough data.
In fact, I know we brought back enough data.
So we were able to build a 50-barrel-a-day fish and drugs plant in Louisiana, Missouri.
And that was largely on the basis of the information we collected in Germany about the plants they operated.
Now, we didn't build that plant exactly like the German plant, because we had some other ideas we had added into it.
I think we had, in fact, at Louisiana Missouri, and during our engineering and construction work out there, had really creamed off the top of what we knew about the fish treatment process.
Now, we also took all of the documents that we could get about the fish, about the coalization process,
And they were all taken to Louisiana, Missouri, all the ones that we thought would be very helpful to us.
And it was on the basis of those documents, plus such assistance as we had from the German people we brought over, by which we designed the collagenation plant at Louisiana, Missouri.
And we made that plant run finally.
And it was pretty much the same type of plant that they had used in Germany.
Now, by the time we had built that plant,
we had a whole lot of new ideas, and we revised the plant considerably and incorporated a lot of those new ideas in it.
Remember now, we're talking about 1945 to 1950, when we've got another 10 or 15 years of technology that we can add in to the German technology to build this plant.
And now, even more than that,

there were documents brought back on processes like the so-called OXO process, in which you can take an unsaturated hydrocarbon compound and add CO and hydrogen to it and make alcohols and ketones and things like that.
And there were several plants built by the oil company on the basis of that technology.

And then the whole acetylene technology, the Germans are quite a long ways ahead of us on the acetylene technology, and the chemical industry picked up the acetylene technology and went into that in quite a lot of detail.

So what I meant was that industry and the Bureau of Mines and everybody in the United States has, in fact, had an awfully good look at this technology and has, in fact, and is now using that technology.
Do I make myself clear?
Sure, you make yourself clear.
What is the Wright-Patterson
Is there a Wright-Patterson system somehow?
Wright-Patterson is the airplane locomotive engine builders.
Yeah.
Would they, for example, have gone back in and looked at the German technology?
I'm sure they did.
Well, I'm not sure of that, but I imagine they had people over there, and I suppose they were interested in the airplane engines and the airplane fuels and things of that nature.
Yeah, I guess.
I want to figure, what, an hour and a half later to the airport?
Yeah, I'd say at least that.
I want to ask you some questions about Louisiana, Missouri plants and problems I had in trying to decide what happened there.
Were there two plants operating there or one plant?
We built both the fissure troops and the coal hydrogenation.
There were two plants.
Two plants, okay.
But they were different size plants.
The coal hydrogenation was 200 barrels a day, and the fissure troops was 50, about one quarter of the size.
Okay.
And did you disassemble a plant and bring it over?
No, no.
We built it, redesigned it, and built it right from scratch.
Okay.
Both cases.
And you used German plans?
Yes.
Modified German plants.
Modified German plants, all right.
Now was there already a plant existing there that you modified?
Yeah, there was.
Louisiana, Missouri was producing ammonia.
Okay.
And we used the part of the ammonia lines to make hydrogen.
We didn't make our own hydrogen for our own coal hydrogenation plant.
We made the hydrogen from natural gas.
And this is where the synthetic fuel was produced, which ran, for example, the terrain.
Yeah.
It comes out of this plant.
And what did you estimate that a plant, how much more efficient was this plant than its comparable German plant?
Well, the actual plant we built probably wasn't much more than 10% or 15% more efficient than a German plant.
But on the basis of what we learned during its construction and operating period,
We designed a plant which I think was about double the efficiency of the German plant.
I assume there's a report where you discuss how efficient this plant would have been.
Yeah, there is.
If I could just put my hand on it right now, I'd give you a copy.
We could make a copy of it.
I probably should have given you...
It's a report by Skinner and Hirsch, as I remember it.
thermal efficiency and we came up with something a little over 55%.
The Germans were about 30% and you were about 55%.
This is a various section of the plant.
Hydrogenation proper, improved plant, German plant, okay.
The hydrogenation proper we came up with about 73 against 51.
The hydrogen manufacturer we came up with.
The Germans were very inefficient in hydrogen manufacturing.
That technology had improved amazingly from 27 to 62.
The power plant from 42 to 39.
The power plant actually went down a little bit.
Overall efficiency, 28.9, and this one is 55.
I see.
And this is what, in the industrial engineering, chemistry?
You want a copy of it?
Yeah.
Let me have the girls make the copy of it for us.
It's selling enough, because the girls are making it.
Good.
Now, so all in all, what percentage of synthetic oil would you say, or what percentage of national production of fuel did the Germans produce through synthetic oils?
I don't know.
I never calculated it.
They produced about 100,000 barrels a day
They're coal-hygienation plants.
And they had seven fish and trout plants.
And I doubt if those seven fish and trout plants produced more than 20,000 barrels a day.
So we're talking 120,000 barrels a day.
And I don't know what their total use is.
You might be able to...
I'm sure you could look it up for those years or the years just before the war, something like that.
But...
At that time, Bob, we were using about 4 million barrels of oil a day, or 4, 4.5 million barrels a day.
I suspect that the Germans were down around 1 million barrels a day, or something in that order.
So it's probably something in the order of 10% to 15% of total production.
Okay?
This is a very rough figure.
Yeah.
So it was only really a supplemental measure, always.
Yeah, and of course what they, there was two things they used this oil for, to a considerable extent.
The coal hydrogenation oil ran a great deal of their Luftwaffe, because it's a high-octane gasoline, mostly.
And the fissure-tropical oil they used for a variety of purposes, but one of the things they used it for was for diesel fuel.
Okay, Mads, thank you very much.
She left a note and I didn't see it.
Yeah.
All right, so there are two plants then.
How much time did you spend at the plant?
Plants?
At the plants.
Did you go to the plants regularly?
When we weren't in London or trying to get from London to Germany, we were in the plants.
Oh, I'm sorry.
I meant the plants in Louisiana, Missouri.
Oh, in Louisiana, Missouri.
Oh, I thought you meant the German plants.
Oh, I used to go out there about...
I guess I was traveling every week.
But, see, I had the Morgantown Laboratory to carry, the Brewston Laboratory, the Louisiana, Missouri plant, and the rifle plant.
So probably once a month, two or three days a month was the best I could do at each place.
Okay, now...
Did the coppers company build one of the plants?
The coppers company built the fish and trout plant.
But the fish and trout plants.
The Bechtel built the coal hydrogenation plant.
Did Bechtel do a cost analysis of both plants?
No, Bechtel only did a cost analysis of the coal hydrogenation plant.
Okay, that's all right.
And I assume they published that.
Yeah, I've got a copy of it here.
Okay.
Now that's all based on 1951 or 1952 figures.
Bob, too.
And then we did our own cost analysis of the Fisher-Tropsch plant.
And was yours substantially different from Bechtel's?
Well, we worked with Bechtel on the analysis of the coal hydrogenation plant.
And so the report that came out from Bechtel was a Bechtel Bureau of Mines report.
Now, later on, we cooperated with the petroleum industry in a study of the coal hydrogenation again.
And that came out a little higher than the Bechtel plant, but substantially in the same region.
Bechtel never analyzed the Fisher Trucks plant.
We did that ourselves.
I don't believe we even had copper samples.
We did meet our own cost analysis.
Fisher Trucks?
Yeah.
If you ask me where that is published, I'd probably have a hell of a time picking my fingers up.
But, you know, this series of reports on synthetic fuels, these annual reports, do have a lot of those cost studies in it for all three things, oil shale, fish, trucks, and coal hydrogenation.
And those annual reports now, those are Bureau of Mines reports?
Those are Bureau of Mines reports, yeah.
From 1946 to 1952.
Yeah, right, right.
I have a few questions on things that were just sort of vague towards the end of our interview that I need to have some information on.
I'll make sure I have these.
And again, I have an advantage over you having both written Tom and having read your interview and you not.
I'm sorry yours didn't arrive here.
It was supposed to have already been here before I got here.
Now, one of the things you say is that I think you've answered the question, all kinds of cost studies have been done.
Are you referring to those in the 1950s and all kinds of cost studies?
But I assume from our conversation, all kinds of cost studies must have been done since the 1950s.
Oh, yes.
Come on in.
Thank you very much.
MR.
Thank you.
Now, will these be summarized in the National Committee of Engineers report?
MR. Only in the most general terminology, Bob.
The economics in that report is not detailed.
It's very, very, there is so much controversy about this economics
we had really to do a sort of an overall job to avoid this controversy.
And as you probably know, IRDA has been making cost studies literally by the dozens since they have been in operation, and the Office of Cold Research made cost studies and everything else.
Let me read you what I said about that.
Bob, these are really my own words, and I think the most nearly represents what I think about the whole damn thing.

Although extensive efforts have been made to accurately determine capital costs for the most promising and most highly developed liquefaction processes, those are really the H coal and the Exxon process now.
The results have shown great variations, depending not only on the process selected but also on the many economic and engineering judgments involved in the estimates.
Furthermore, estimating has been made much more difficult by the inflation that has occurred during the last five years, and it is necessary to talk in terms of ranges rather than specific figures.

Estimates indicate that the capital cost of the most promising of the coal liquefaction processes, and I'm not referring to dry coal hydrogenation, I'm just referring to the existing processes, to produce a synthetic crude oil from a plant feeding 25,000 to 50,000 tons of coal per day will fall... No, there's an error there, isn't there?
Well, I think they want to check that.
Will fall in the range of $20,000 to $30,000 per barrel per operating day.
And that's about five times what a petroleum refinery costs.
Well, the cost of product will depend mainly on the capital and operating costs of the plant.
An additional important factor is the cost of the coal.
With coals priced from 40 to 120 per million BTUs, that's in the range from about $8 to $25 a ton.
The corresponding cost of synthetic crude is $20 to $30 per barrel.
And I think that's too low.
I think it's probably closer to $30 to $40 a barrel, particularly since this date is a year old now.
Yeah.
Harry?
And so you think then $30 to $40 a barrel is more realistic?
Of course, synthetic crude.
Of course, synthetic crude.
Okay.
Now, you say that we have, in fact, reviewed every process that is publicly described for either the fissure tropes or the cold hydrogenation process.
My tongue has become thick this afternoon.
All right.
Now, is this the...
Were you referring to the TOM documents here?
No, no, I'm referring to the Academy of Engineering.
To the Academy of Engineering?
Yeah.
Okay.
All right.
Does that include going back and looking at German documents?
That's out of curiosity.
No, because we felt that the processes now have proceeded somewhat beyond the German technology.
Now...
Is there any way to find out where all the reports were distributed by Major Green?
Do you have any idea?
I remember Major Green.
He evidently distributed.
Was he with the Department of Commerce?
Yes.
No, I have no idea, Bob, how you could find that out.
Unless it's in the records of the Department of Commerce someplace.
Well, I can check with them.
And then I somehow or another have come up with five indexes, which we've spoken of before.
going to 1 to 119, then 119 went to 450, and then a last index, which goes on to 305.
And you didn't have anything to do with putting these indexes together?
No.
OK. Then you can't answer my questions on how they counted documents.
I'm trying to arrive at a total figure of the number of documents
brought into this country, see?
And they seem to be scattered all over the country, and I can't...
I'm sure you're right.
You know, I can't seem to find... For example, there are documents at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base.
Were those documents I had on coal hydrogenation, were they from Wright-Patterson?
No, this is a central air documents office.
And that was... And I don't know what the Air Force did over there.
I've got a few of the things they did, as you see here, but I have no idea how much work they did.
Well, I...
